Description (Purpose of business):
The Action Request Forms (ARF) is an in-house developed web application deployed to the CEC intranet.  The database consists of a number of ‘tickets’ primarily generated by Information Officers while using the IMPACT 6.0 application.  An ARF ticket is a mechanism for informing the ICM of potential day-to-day database maintenance issues since changes can occur between updating periods.  This application flags the precise ‘piece’ of data as displayed in IMPACT 6.0 that is in need of attention from the Information Management Officers, such as changes in telephone numbers, website addresses or office closures.

The ARF system is used to:
•	Relay enquiries from callers that require further research by the ICM;
•	Report incorrect or questionable information in the databases to the ICM (grammar, spelling, information that differs from a GC website, out-dated information, reported existence of a new program with no info, etc.);
•	Communicate suggestions for improving the repositories to the ICM;
•	The ARF ticketing system is also integrated into the IMPACT 6.0 application.  ARF tickets can be created directly from the IMPACT 6.0 application and will provide a precise reference to the exact piece of data that is in question;
•	Provides linked data from the IMS databases to ensure accuracy of reporting.

ARF is an Intranet website for informing the ICM of potential day-to-day database maintenance issues.

Provide a system of connected Infrastructure that enables the hosts to change, and the hosts to change out their software tools with minimal impacts to clients of web management related tools: tools for the management of web content, tools to search the managed web content, and tools to present the web content.   Basically provide a content services platform as a service. 

The Enterprise Web Content Management System (EWCMS) currently hosts the COTS software of TeamSite Suite (TeamSite, OpenDeploy, TeamSite Search, TeamSite Advanced Reports and LiveSite supported by an Oracle Database) for content mangment, and IDOL Search to provide Enterprise Search capabilities, and MS IIS services plus Oracle HTTP services plus Oracle Welogic services for various web presentations of the web content on one of many hosts that are part of the solution.

At present there are 3 production implementations, each is composed of 3 parts:

- EWCMS-Web Content Management Stream: Authoring, Publishing & Reporting {TeamSite, OpenDeploy, TeamSite Search, (optional) LiveSite} 
- EWCMS-Web Delivery Stream: Web Display {IIS, OHS,  OpenDeploy, (optional) LiveSite Display}
- EWCMS-Enterprise Search Stream: Search {OpenDeploy, HP IDOL Search}

The EWCMS supports client driven Internet/Intranet/ExtraNet website content creation including support for WET 4, with on-demand publication to multiple platforms eliminating both costly infrastructure duplication and compliancy issues. The authoring tier while required for updating website content, may be taken off-line without impacting the published content. IDOL Search is leveraged to give Search functionality to the web tier sites and applications.

